The following article delves into the intricacies of [Omega](/Omega_(disambiguation)), the ultimate letter of the [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet).

"Ω" redirects here, as if you couldn't deduce its primary significance. For the unit of electrical resistance, a rather mundane application, one might refer to [Ohm](/Ohm).
This particular exposition focuses on the [Greek letter](/Category:Greek_letters) itself. Should your interest be diverted to its [Cyrillic](/Omega_(Cyrillic)) counterpart, a distinct article awaits. Similarly, for the [Latin](/Latin_omega) adaptation, another path is provided.
For a broader collection of interpretations, should your mind demand further categorization, consult the [Omega (disambiguation)](/Omega_(disambiguation)) page.

This article, like most human endeavors, could benefit from more robust [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). It seems the foundational elements of knowledge often require constant shoring up. Therefore, if you possess an unusual compulsion to [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Omega), consider [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_begins). Unsubstantiated claims, much like unchecked human ambition, are prone to challenge and eventual removal. Should you find yourself with an abundance of time and a shortage of more pressing existential concerns, you might endeavor to find sources via news, newspapers, books, scholar databases, or [JSTOR](/JSTOR) (as of December 2014). For those who struggle with the basic mechanics of such tasks, a guide exists on [how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal).

