[Omega](/Omega_(disambiguation)) (pronounced, with varying degrees of confidence, as [/oʊˈmeɪɡə, -ˈmɛɡə, -ˈmiːɡə/](/Help:IPA/English) in [American English](/American_English) &#32; [ⓘ](/File:LL-Q1860_(eng)-Flame,_not_lame-Omega.wav) , and [/ˈoʊmɪɡə/](/Help:IPA/English) in [British English](/British_English) &#91;1&#93;), is the twenty-fourth and, rather tellingly, the *last* letter in the venerable [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet). It holds a certain finality, a definitive closure that few other letters can claim. In the arcane practices of the [Greek numeric system](/Greek_numerals) or [isopsephy](/Isopsephy) (a system often conflated with [gematria](/Gematria)), this letter is assigned a numerical value of 800. The original designation for this letter was a simple ὦ ( ō̂ [&#91;ɔ̂ː&#93;](/Help:IPA/Greek)). However, in a rather unsurprising act of human linguistic evolution, this was later altered in the Middle Ages to ὦ μέγα ( ō̂ méga ), which translates, with a stunning lack of imagination, to 'big o'. This modification was deemed necessary to differentiate it from [omicron](/Omicron) &#x27e8;ο&#x27e9;, whose name, equally plainly, means 'small o'. The irony, of course, is that both letters eventually converged in pronunciation to [&#91;o&#93;](/Help:IPA), rendering the original distinction moot in modern usage &#91;2&#93;. In the contemporary linguistic landscape of [modern Greek](/Modern_Greek), the name has predictably fused into ωμέγα ( oméga ).

From a [phonetic](/Phonetics) perspective, the [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) capital letter Ω represented a [long](/Vowel_length) [open-mid back rounded vowel](/Open-mid_back_rounded_vowel), specifically [&#91;ɔː&#93;](/Help:IPA/Greek). This stood in stark contrast to its supposed "small" counterpart, [omicron](/Omicron), which articulated the [close-mid back rounded vowel](/Close-mid_back_rounded_vowel) [&#91;o&#93;](/Help:IPA/Greek). Further complicating matters for anyone attempting to master ancient pronunciations, the [digraph](/Digraph_(orthography)) &#x27e8;ου&#x27e9; was employed to represent the [long](/Vowel_length) [close back rounded vowel](/Close_back_rounded_vowel) [&#91;uː&#93;](/Help:IPA/Greek). Fast forward to [modern Greek](/Modern_Greek), and this once clear distinction has, like so many things, blurred into a singular, undifferentiated sound: both omega and omicron now represent the [mid back rounded vowel](/Mid_back_rounded_vowel) [&#91;o̞&#93;](/Help:IPA/Greek). When [transliterated](/Transliteration) into a [Latin-script alphabet](/Latin-script_alphabet), the letter omega is typically rendered as ō or, for the truly uninspired, simply o.

Given its position as the ultimate letter in the [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet), omega has, perhaps inevitably, been appropriated to signify the last, the end, or the ultimate limit of a [set](/Set_theory). This stands in direct opposition to [alpha](/Alpha_(letter)), the first letter, which predictably denotes the beginning. This symbolic pairing, often invoked with a solemnity that belies its linguistic origin, is best explored under the concept of [Alpha and Omega](/Alpha_and_Omega). Humanity's obsession with beginnings and endings, neatly packaged into two convenient symbols.

## History

Remarkably, Ω was conspicuously absent from the earlier iterations of the [Greek alphabets](/Archaic_Greek_alphabets) during the 8th century BC. It made its rather belated entrance in the late 7th century BC within the vibrant [Ionian](/Ionia) cities of [Asia Minor](/Asia_Minor). Its purpose was quite specific: to represent a [long](/Vowel_length) [open-mid back rounded vowel](/Open-mid_back_rounded_vowel), specifically [ɔː]. Its form is not some grand, original design, but a prosaic variant of [omicron](/Omicron) (Ο), initially broken up at the side ( ) and subsequently having its edges turned outward ( , , , ). One might almost call it a lazy evolution. Interestingly, the [Dorian](/Dorians) city of [Knidos](/Knidos), along with a scattering of [Aegean islands](/Aegean_Islands) such as [Paros](/Paros), [Thasos](/Thasos), and [Melos](/Melos), chose a path of deliberate contrarianism. They embraced the exact opposite convention, utilizing a broken-up circle for the short 'o' and a closed circle for the long /o/ &#91;3&#93;. An admirable, if ultimately futile, attempt at individuality.

The name Ωμέγα itself is a product of the [Byzantine](/Medieval_Greek) era. In the more refined epoch of [Classical Greek](/Ancient_Greek), the letter was simply known as ō (ὦ), pronounced with the distinct /ɔ̂ː/. Meanwhile, its diminutive cousin, omicron, was referred to as ou (οὖ), pronounced /ôː/ &#91;4&#93;. The modern lowercase shape of omega, that familiar ω, can be traced back to the [uncial](/Uncial) form, a somewhat squashed variant that emerged during the 3rd century BC. This particular shape developed in ancient handwriting on [papyrus](/Papyrus), evolving from an even more flattened-out form of the letter ( ) whose edges had been curved further upward &#91;5&#93;. A testament to the relentless march of ergonomic efficiency, even in ancient script.

Beyond its Greek origins, Omega found its way into other linguistic systems. It was adopted into the [early Cyrillic alphabet](/Early_Cyrillic_alphabet), giving rise to the [Cyrillic omega](/Omega_(Cyrillic)) (Ѡ, ѡ). Furthermore, a [Raetic](/Raetic_alphabet) variant is widely conjectured to be either the direct ancestor or a parallel evolutionary branch of the [Elder Futhark](/Elder_Futhark) [ᛟ](/%E1%9B%9F) rune. And, in a demonstration of its enduring if niche utility, Omega was even incorporated into the [Latin alphabet](/Latin_alphabet) as part of the 1982 revision to the [African reference alphabet](/African_reference_alphabet). Its usage there remains, predictably, sparse (see [Latin omega](/Latin_omega)).

## The symbol Ω (uppercase letter)

A [plaque in Kos](/Kos) with what appears to be an "underlined O" form of omega. A rather quaint variation.

The [uppercase](/Upper_case) letter Ω has, over time, been pressed into service as a symbol across a bewildering array of disciplines, each attempting to quantify or categorize some aspect of the universe.

*   In [chemistry](/Chemistry):
    *   It designates [oxygen-18](/Oxygen-18), a naturally occurring, stable [isotope](/Isotope) of [oxygen](/Oxygen). A specific label for a specific atom, as if the universe needed more identifiers &#91;6&#93;.
    *   It represents the [omega loop](/Omega_loop), a protein structural motif characterized by a loop comprising six or more [amino acid](/Amino_acid) residues in any sequence. Its name, in a rare moment of clarity, is derived from its visual resemblance to the Greek letter &#91;7&#93;.

*   In [physics](/Physics):
    *   Most famously, it is the symbol for the [ohm](/Ohm) – the [SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) of [electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance). Unicode, in its infinite wisdom, provides a separate code point, U+2126&#x20;&#x2126; OHM SIGN ([HTML entity](/HTML_entity) &ohm; ), which exists purely for the sake of backward compatibility. The canonically correct, and therefore preferred, code point is U+03A9&#x20;&#x3a9; GREEK CAPITAL LETTER OMEGA ( &Omega; ). This level of bureaucratic pedantry in character encoding is truly breathtaking. Furthermore, it was formerly used in an inverted form (U+2127&#x20;&#x2127; INVERTED OHM SIGN) to represent the [mho](/Mho), the archaic term for the inverse of an ohm, now more elegantly (and less confusingly) known as the [siemens](/Siemens) with the symbol S &#91;9&#93;.
    *   In the esoteric realm of [statistical mechanics](/Statistical_mechanics), Ω is employed to denote the [multiplicity](/Multiplicity_(physics)), which is essentially the number of possible [microstates](/Microstate_(statistical_mechanics)) within a given system. A way to count the infinite possibilities, I suppose.
    *   It can signify the [solid angle](/Solid_angle) &#91;10&#93;&#91;11&#93; or the rate of [precession](/Precession) within a [gyroscope](/Gyroscope). Because everything must be quantified, even rotational wobble.
    *   In the bewildering field of [particle physics](/Particle_physics), it represents the [Omega baryons](/Omega_baryon), a class of subatomic particles.
    *   Within [astronomy](/Astronomy) (specifically [cosmology](/Cosmology)), Ω refers to the average density of the universe, elegantly termed the [density parameter](/Density_parameter). A rather grand aspiration for a single letter.
    *   In [astronomy](/Astronomy) (specifically [orbital mechanics](/Orbital_mechanics)), Ω denotes the [longitude of the ascending node](/Longitude_of_the_ascending_node) of an orbit &#91;12&#93;. Another celestial coordinate, another symbol.

*   In [mathematics](/Mathematics) and [computer science](/Computer_science):
    *   In the complex realm of [complex analysis](/Complex_analysis), it signifies the [Omega constant](/Omega_constant), a specific solution derived from [Lambert's W function](/Lambert_W_function) &#91;13&#93;.
    *   In [differential geometry](/Differential_geometry), it represents the space of [differential forms](/Differential_form) on a [manifold](/Manifold) (typically of a certain degree, often indicated by a superscript).
    *   It serves as a variable for a 2-dimensional region in [calculus](/Calculus), usually defining the domain over which a [double integral](/Multiple_integral) is performed. A convenient placeholder for arbitrary boundaries.
    *   In [topos theory](/Topos_theory), it refers to the (codomain of the) [subobject classifier](/Subobject_classifier) of an [elementary topos](/Elementary_topos). For those who find joy in such abstract constructions.
    *   In [combinatory logic](/Combinatory_logic), it represents the looping combinator, specifically (S I I (S I I)). A testament to the self-referential nature of some logical systems.
    *   In [group theory](/Group_theory), it denotes the [omega and agemo subgroups](/Omega_and_agemo_subgroup) of a [p-group](/p-group), specifically Ω( *G* ) and ℧( *G* ).
    *   Also in [group theory](/Group_theory), it is used in [Cayley's Ω process](/Cayley%27s_%CE%A9_process) as a partial differential operator.
    *   In [statistics](/Statistics), it is the chosen symbol for the [sample space](/Sample_space), which encompasses the total set of all possible outcomes. A rather optimistic symbol for the unpredictable nature of reality.
    *   In [triangle geometry](/Triangle_geometry), it identifies the [Brocard points](/Brocard_points) &#91;14&#93;.
    *   In [number theory](/Number_theory), Ω(*n*) quantifies the total number of [prime divisors](/Prime_divisor) of *n*, crucially counting their [multiplicity](/Multiplicity_(mathematics)) &#91;15&#93;.
    *   In notation related to [Big O notation](/Big_O_notation), it describes the [asymptotic behavior](/Asymptotic_analysis) of functions, specifically a lower bound &#91;16&#93;.
    *   It represents [Chaitin's constant](/Chaitin%27s_constant) &#91;17&#93;, a rather profound and uncomputable number.
    *   In [set theory](/Set_theory), it can refer to the [first uncountable ordinal number](/First_uncountable_ordinal), often written as ω<sub>1</sub> or Ω.
    *   It symbolizes the [absolute infinite](/Absolute_infinite), a concept proposed by the mathematician [Georg Cantor](/Georg_Cantor). A rather ambitious designation, if you ask me.

*   As part of a logo or trademark, because even the ultimate letter can be reduced to branding:
    *   The distinguished logo of [Omega Watches](/Omega_Watches) SA &#91;18&#93;.
    *   An integral component of the original [Pioneer Corporation](/Pioneer_Corporation) logo, often depicted as a tuning fork encircled by the Greek letter &#91;19&#93;.
    *   Part of the [Badge of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom), where it is surrounded by the plant badges of England, Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland, symbolizing ultimate authority &#91;20&#93;.
    *   Featured prominently in the mission patch for [STS-135](/STS-135), serving as a poignant acknowledgment that it was the final mission of the Space Shuttle program. Humanity's sentimental attachment to endings, laid bare &#91;21&#93;.
    *   The striking logo of the [God of War](/God_of_War_(franchise)) video game series, a franchise steeped in [Greek mythology](/Greek_mythology). In *God of War (2018)*, it is explicitly revealed to symbolize war itself in ancient Greece.
    *   The distinctive logo of [E-123 Omega](/E-123_Omega), a character from the [Sonic the Hedgehog](/Sonic_the_Hedgehog) universe.
    *   The logo for the [Heroes of Olympus](/Heroes_of_Olympus) series, another modern interpretation drawing upon Greek mythology.
    *   The heraldic emblem of the [Ultramarines](/Space_Marines_(Warhammer_40,000)) in the grimdark universe of [Warhammer 40,000](/Warhammer_40,000).
    *   The version mascot logo for [Primal Groudon](/Groudon), featured in [Pokémon Omega Ruby](/Pok%C3%A9mon_Omega_Ruby).
    *   The iconic symbol of [Darkseid](/Darkseid) within [DC Comics](/DC_Comics).
    *   One of the personal logos of the professional wrestler [Kenny Omega](/Kenny_Omega).
    *   The logo for [Meow Wolf](/Meow_Wolf)'s [Omega Mart](/Omega_Mart) installation in Area15, Las Vegas, Nevada.
    *   The logo of the [Lalaji Memorial Omega International School](/Lalaji_Memorial_Omega_International_School).

*   Other, miscellaneous uses, because the universe abhors a vacuum:
    *   An [Omega-shaped entrance to the Panteón de la Cruz in Aguascalientes](/Aguascalientes_(city)), which rather directly represents the end of life &#91;22&#93;. A subtle touch, that.
    *   In [eschatology](/Eschatology), the theological study of final events, it serves as a potent symbol for the ultimate conclusion of all things, the inevitable end.
    *   In the intricate world of [molecular biology](/Molecular_biology), the symbol is used as a shorthand to denote a [genetic construct](/Genetic_construct) introduced via a [two-point crossover](/Crossover_(genetic_algorithm)).
    *   The elusive Omega Particle within the expansive [Star Trek universe](/The_Omega_Directive) &#91;23&#93;.
    *   The final, most challenging form of NetNavi bosses in some of the [Mega Man Battle Network](/Mega_Man_Battle_Network) video games.
    *   A secret, often formidable, boss in the long-running [Final Fantasy](/Final_Fantasy) series, known simply as Omega ( Ω ) Weapon.
    *   A character from the venerable [Doctor Who](/Doctor_Who) series named Omega, widely believed to be one of the original architects of the [Time Lords](/Time_Lord) of [Gallifrey](/Gallifrey).
    *   The symbol for the highest conceivable power level of a [PSI](/Psionics) attack in the beloved [Mother](/Mother_(video_game_series))/[EarthBound](/EarthBound) video games.
    *   A symbol adopted by U.S. citizens during the 1960s and 1970s to signify resistance to the [U.S. war in Viet Nam](/Vietnam_War), cleverly adapted from the [SI unit](/International_System_of_Units) for electrical resistance &#91;24&#93;. A rather clever, if ultimately ineffective, act of defiance.
    *   It is paired with [Alpha](/Alpha) in the profound [Alpha and Omega](/Alpha_and_Omega), a pervasive Christian symbol representing God as the beginning and the end &#91;25&#93;.
    *   Used to denote the [highest tier](/Rank) of equipment in the rather simplistic [flash game](/Browser_game), *Learn to Fly*.
    *   Appears in the film [Galaxy Quest](/Galaxy_Quest) as the enigmatic [Omega 13 device](/Omega_13_device).

## The symbol ω (lowercase letter)

The [minuscule](/Lower_case) letter ω, perhaps less overtly dramatic than its uppercase sibling, is nonetheless employed as a symbol across a considerable range of fields, often with a more technical, less existential, connotation.

*   Biology, biochemistry, and chemistry:
    *   In [biochemistry](/Biochemistry), it designates one of the subunits of [RNA polymerase](/RNA_polymerase), a crucial enzyme.
    *   In [biology](/Biology), it quantifies [fitness](/Fitness_(biology)), a measure of reproductive success. A rather cold assessment of life, really.
    *   In [chemistry](/Chemistry), it indicates the carbon atom positioned furthest from the [carboxyl group](/Carboxyl_group) of a [fatty acid](/Fatty_acid), a structural detail of some importance.
    *   In [genomics](/Genomics), it serves as a metric for [molecular evolution](/Molecular_evolution) in [protein-coding genes](/Protein-coding_gene) (also commonly denoted as d<sub>N</sub>/d<sub>S</sub> or K<sub>a</sub>/K<sub>s</sub> ratio). A way to track the slow, relentless march of genetic change.

*   Physics:
    *   It represents [angular velocity](/Angular_velocity) or [angular frequency](/Angular_frequency) &#91;26&#93;. The speed of rotation, for those who need to measure such things.
    *   It can denote rotational velocity (when bolded) or [rotational speed or frequency](/Rotational_frequency) &#91;27&#93;.
    *   In [computational fluid dynamics](/Computational_fluid_dynamics), it signifies the specific turbulence dissipation rate, a rather specialized measure of chaotic motion.
    *   In [meteorology](/Meteorology), it describes the change of pressure with respect to time for a [parcel](/Fluid_parcel) of air. A way to quantify atmospheric dynamics.
    *   In [circuit analysis](/Circuit_analysis) and [signal processing](/Signal_processing), it represents [angular frequency](/Angular_frequency), a concept intrinsically linked to [frequency](/Frequency) *f* by the simple relation ω = 2π*f*.
    *   In [astronomy](/Astronomy), it is used as a ranking to denote a star's brightness within a given [constellation](/Constellation) &#91;28&#93;. Though, as with many human systems, there are numerous exceptions to this rule.
    *   In [orbital mechanics](/Orbital_mechanics), it is the designation for the [argument of periapsis](/Argument_of_periapsis) of an orbit &#91;12&#93;. Another parameter to define the endless dance of celestial bodies.
    *   In [particle physics](/Particle_physics), it represents the [omega meson](/Meson) &#91;29&#93;.

*   Computer science:
    *   In notation related to [Big O notation](/Big_O_notation), it describes the asymptotically dominant nature of [functions](/Function_(mathematics)), essentially providing a lower bound.
    *   In [relational database](/Relational_database) theory, it is used to represent [NULL](/Null_(SQL)), a missing or inapplicable value. A placeholder for the absence of information.
    *   In [APL (programming language)](/APL_(programming_language)), it represents the right parameter passed to a function.

*   Mathematics:
    *   The first and smallest [transfinite](/Transfinite_number) [ordinal number](/Ordinal_number), often quaintly identified with the set of [natural numbers](/Natural_number) including 0 (and sometimes, for clarity, written as ω<sub>0</sub>) &#91;30&#93;&#91;31&#93;.
    *   In [set theory](/Set_theory), ω is indeed the [ordinal number](/Ordinal_number) &#91;32&#93;.
    *   A primitive [root of unity](/Roots_of_unity), such as the complex cube roots of 1.
    *   The [Wright Omega function](/Wright_Omega_function) &#91;33&#93;.
    *   A generic [differential form](/Differential_form).
    *   In [number theory](/Number_theory), ω(*n*) counts the number of *distinct* [prime divisors](/Prime_divisor) of *n* &#91;34&#93;.
    *   Also in [number theory](/Number_theory), it can represent an [arithmetic function](/Arithmetic_function).
    *   In [combinatory logic](/Combinatory_logic), it denotes the self-application combinator, (λ *x*. *x x*).
    *   In [triangle geometry](/Triangle_geometry), it represents a [Brocard angle](/Brocard_angle) &#91;35&#93;.
    *   The [clique number](/Clique_number) in [Graph theory](/Graph_theory) &#91;36&#93;.

*   Finance:
    *   In the complex world of [finance](/Finance), it represents the elasticity of [options](/Option_(finance)).
    *   In analytical investment management, it denotes the [tracking error](/Tracking_error) of an investment manager. A measure of how well a portfolio mirrors its benchmark, or how badly it deviates.

*   Other, perhaps less critical, applications:
    *   Used in place of [ん](/N_(kana)) in Japanese typing shorthand, a testament to efficiency in communication.
    *   In [linguistics](/Linguistics), it represents the [phonological word](/Phonological_word).
    *   In [textual criticism](/Textual_criticism), it identifies the [archetype](/Archetype) of a manuscript tradition, the theoretical original from which all copies derive.
    *   In [sociology](/Sociology), it is occasionally used to refer to the lowest ranking member of a group &#91;37&#93;. A rather blunt label for social stratification.
    *   In [economics](/Economics) (particularly within [general equilibrium theory](/General_equilibrium_theory)), it signifies the endowments of agents.
    *   In [Shift_JIS art](/Shift_JIS_art), it is charmingly used to represent a cat's mouth (e.g., (´･ω･`) ｼｮﾎﾞｰﾝ). A rare moment of whimsicality for this austere letter.
    *   In [actuarial sciences](/Actuarial_science), it represents the maximum life span that characterizes a [mortality table](/Mortality_table) &#91;38&#93;. A stark reminder of humanity's finite nature, encapsulated in a single symbol.

